[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:A9742.A983.K6.Q7 J.Q64.AJ843.T984 K8.JT7.975.AKJ62 QT653.K52.QT2.53"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1S Pass 2C Pass 2H Pass 3D =1= Pass 3NT Pass Pass Pass
[Note "1:4th suit"]
{North opens 1\S- how do you respond?
With 14 points, you respond 2\C, a natural 2/1 force to game.
North next bids 2\H, showing the other Major suit.  What do you rebid now?
You assume North to be 5-4 in the Majors, so you cannot support either.  You cannot bid 2NT without a stopper in \Ds. So you bid the fourth suit, 3\D, telling North you knows you must make a bid, but can't find anything appropriate.  This is an artificial bid, and normally denies a diamond stopper (otherwise you would have bid 2NT).
North rebids 3NT - what do you do now?

North now must find a bid. His choices include rebidding the 5-card \Ss, supporting South's \Cs with a doubleton Queen, or bidding 3NT with the \D K 6 as a stopper. He chooses this last option. It appears that 3NT is the best game for these two hands.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "2"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "W:KJ763.AQ7.84.AQJ T9852.942.T5.KT6 A4.KJT8653.KQ.87 Q..AJ97632.95432"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6H"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "W"]
1S Pass 2H Pass 3H Pass 3S =1= Pass 4C =2= Pass 4NT Pass 5S =3= Pass 6H Pass Pass Pass
[Note "1:control"]
[Note "2:control"]
[Note "3:2 keycards + trump Q"]
{How do you open the bidding?
With 18 HCP and a balanced hand, you open 1\S.  Partner responds  2\H. What do you rebid?
You know this is a 5-card suit, and bid 3\H, confirming the 8+card trump fit and sets the trump suit.
Partner rebids 3\S, a control bid, showing first or second round control.  (Some will play this as showing 3-card support for spades, but I recommend playing this as a control bid.).  
You bid 4C, also a control bid, showing first or second round control in clubs.  Partner bids 4NT, a keycard request using 1430.   

You bid 5\s, showing two keycards and the trump queen.  Partner bids the slam.
The slam is a good one. If either the \SQ or \CK is right there are 12 tricks by way of a finesse. But the best way to play the hand would be to try to establish a \S in the West hand, and if that fails try the \C finesse.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:Q9752.JT6.T32.93 AJT.AK985.K96.Q7 K4.Q42.J875.8652 863.73.AQ4.AKJT4"]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "6NT"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "E"]
Pass 1H Pass 2C Pass 2NT Pass 3NT Pass 4NT Pass 6NT Pass Pass Pass
{South opens 1\H and North responds 2\C. Using standard bidding South would now jump to 3NT to show his 19 points, but in 2/1 this is not necessary since the partnership must not stop bidding until game is reached. So South just bids 2NT. North shows her minimum by bidding 3NT.
South will now disclose his extra strength. He bids 4NT. This is not Blackwood, but rather a quantitative raise in Notrump, and an invitation to slam.
North has 15 points, and they are good ones. She accepts the invitation and bids 6NT.
There are 11 top tricks. A 3-3 \H split would provide the 12th winner, but this is against the odds. Better to try two \S finesses, a 75% chance.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "S:T94.8764.T82.KQ3 AJ8752.AK.Q6.J87 K.JT952.753.AT52 Q63.Q3.AKJ94.964"]
[Declarer "W"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "S"]
Pass 1S Pass 2D Pass 2S Pass 4S Pass Pass Pass
{West opens 1\S -  
You responds 2\D, natural and game forcing.  West rebids 2\s.  In our style of 2/1, this promises 6+ cards in spades, and denies a side 4-card suit.  What should we bid now? 

You should jump to 4\S. This is Fast Arrival, indicating a minimum hand with no particular interest in slam.
West is happy to rest in the game contract.
Even with a combined 30 points, 10 tricks are certainly not a sure thing. West must hope that South holds the trump King.}

